On 6/10/2017 at 0:44 AM, lindemherz said:

To think those crazy stand-up guys actually thought of it...

Glad someone knew what I was going for! I was planning on flying an Apollo and a Soyuz out to it as well, but I got sick and at any rate, there were some errors with the textures on my Apollo I didn't have time to fix.

Tried the latest release, 1.2.2 compatibility confirmed  Also, here's some more international cooperation:

First, there was a contract to build a space station in Mun's orbit. And there was one N-1 with your typical Munar mission (dubbed Hermes) on top of it, collecting dust in some far corner of the space center with no actual tasks to fly and do. And from these, the Demeter mission was born.
 

Spoiler

 

Repurposing the rocket was a breeze. So, on this Munar mission we have an N-1 carrier...

...with a Gemini on top! Why? Because it's light, plus we don't need a scientist this time. They will arrive a few missions later.

Engine start...

...and liftoff! Launchpad cleared, first stage burning with no unplanned explosions!

Coasting to apoapsis...

Burning to circularise... Well, no. It's actually the start of the transmunar burn. 'Cuz we're on Kerbin. Stock Kerbin.

Stage separation. Mind the bug: the engine shrouds still jetisson the wrong way.

Fairing sep. That's no lander, that's a space station!

Orbital reassembly. You'd think it's a breeze to perform on a Gemini...

...But the flight computer locked up and refused to accept any targets! Me horrible pilot, me can't dock without a docking aid.

In the end, the station's autopilot had to be turned on. Thankfully, this one had no such problem.

Assembly continues! Jonble, our ever-heroic engineer, goes on EVA to attach some...

...trusses. What? We always need a truss.

Or two. And a couple solar panels.

Or a couple couples.

After some desparate attempts to make the ship's computer target anything, the crew realize they're dead weight here and depart back to Kerbin.

Meanwhile, the Demeter station proceeds to pick up a couple landers from previous Hermes missions – for habitation and as possible future Munar shuttles (and that's the reason why we brought N1's third stage and its hulking fuel tank all the way) and then moves from the 14 degrees inclined orbit to the more comfortable equatorial one. Most of it was happening on the night side, but here's a nice shot.

The end? Well, not really. Valentina and Jonble are here very busy hoping not to burn in the atmosphere or lose the parachute and saying many nice words to whoever balanced their Gemini. Thankfully, there's a happy end for them.
